# Taskflow

<ph One-line project tagline — lightweight, fast, developer-friendly distributed task queue.>

<context tech_stack>
- Language: Rust (core) + Python bindings (PyO3)
- Message broker: Redis or NATS
- Serialization: MessagePack
- Minimum supported Rust version: 1.75
- Python version: 3.10+
</context tech_stack>

<context architecture>
Taskflow follows a worker-pool architecture:
- Producers submit tasks to a broker (Redis or NATS)
- Workers pull tasks from queues, execute handlers, and report results
- A scheduler component handles delayed and periodic (cron) tasks
- Results are stored in Redis with configurable TTL
- Workers support graceful shutdown, retry with exponential backoff, and dead-letter queues
</context architecture>

## Features

@- Distributed task execution with automatic load balancing
- Redis and NATS broker support
- Task priorities, deadlines, and rate limiting
- Cron-style periodic tasks
- Automatic retries with exponential backoff
- Dead-letter queues for failed tasks
- Real-time task monitoring dashboard@<param context:tech_stack;architecture><prompt Review and expand this feature list. Add 3-4 more features that a production-grade task queue should have (think: observability, security, developer experience). Format as a markdown bullet list with brief descriptions for each feature.>

## Installation

### Rust

\`\`\`toml
[dependencies]
taskflow = "0.8"
\`\`\`

### Python

\`\`\`bash
pip install taskflow-py
\`\`\`

The Python package requires <ph minimum Python version> and ships pre-built
wheels for Linux (x86\_64, aarch64), macOS (universal2), and Windows (x86\_64).

## Quick Start

### Rust

\`\`\`rust
use taskflow::prelude::*;

\#[tokio::main]
async fn main() -\> Result\<()\> {
    let broker = RedisBroker::connect("redis://localhost:6379").await?;
    let mut worker = Worker::new(broker);

    worker.register("send_email", |task: Task| async move {
        let email: Email = task.deserialize()?;
        send_email(&email).await?;
        Ok(())
    });

    worker.start().await
}
\`\`\`

### Python

\`\`\`python
from taskflow import Broker, Worker

broker = Broker("redis://localhost:6379")
worker = Worker(broker)

\@worker.task(name="send_email", retries=3)
async def send_email(to: str, subject: str, body: str):
    # your email logic here
    pass

if __name__ == "__main__":
    worker.run()
\`\`\`

